content.problemStatement:
The `this` keyword in Java differentiates between class fields (`instance variables`) and `method parameters` when they share the same name. It refers to the current instance of the class and is used to access class fields in constructors and methods.

**Syntax:**
```java
class ClassName {
    dataType variableName;  // Field declaration

    // Parameterized constructor
    public ClassName(dataType variableName) {
        this.variableName = variableName;  // Refers to the class field
    }
}
```
---
**Example:**
```java
class Seedit {
    String name;
    int age;

    // Parameterized constructor to initialize name and age
    public SEED-IT(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;  // 'this' refers to the class field
        this.age = age;    // 'this' refers to the class field
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create an object using the parameterized constructor
        SEED-IT student = new SEED-IT("Ram", 30);

        // Display the student's name and age directly inside main
        System.out.println("Name: " + student.name);  // Accessing class field using object reference
        System.out.println("Age: " + student.age);    // Accessing class field using object reference
    }
}

```
**Expected Output:**
```default
Name: Ram
Age: 30
```

